-- S.Africa fines top four banks over anti-money laundering controls
-- By Helen Nyambura-Mwaura
-- Wed Apr 16, 2014 04:32AM EDT
-- None



JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Reuters) - South Africa's Reserve Bank said on Wednesday it had had fined the country's top four banks a total 125 million rand ($11.8 million) over lax anti-money laundering controls.

The central bank said in a statement it had fined the South African unit of Barclays Africa Group <BGAJ.J> 10 million rand, FirstRand <FSRJ.J> 30 million rand, Nedbank <NEDJ.J> 25 million rand and market leader Standard Bank <SBKJ.J> 60 million rand.